RED HILL SUPERIOR RESIDENTIAL SUBURB Private Enterprise Moving EXTENSIVE BUILDING FORESHADOWED From the commencement, Red Hill has been regarded as a suburb apart, and its situation and general characteristics stamped it as the locality where would be seated higher class residentials of Canberra. This estimate of Red Hill has been maintained and the class of residence which is being erected there and for which plans are being prepared is somewhat different from the general class of residential raised in other parts of the city. Development has been somewhat slow to date and few houses only dot the still grassy virgin slopes, but within the next few weeks private enterprise has to accomplish considerable activity and a large number of houses will be commenced. It is possible to state that on every lease in the original subdivision of Red Hill, building operations will be commenced before the end of the year.

title: CANBERRA'S RAILWAY EARLY CONSIDERATION IMPERATIVE MANY ALTERNATIVE ROUTES Immediate consideration by the Public Works Committee of railway communication with Canberra has become a matter of vital concern to the development of the city. Recently a survey was made of a proposed railway line on the northern side of the river at Canberra, but no announcement has been made regarding the intentions of the Department of Works and Railways in this connection. The question of a railway to connect Canberra with the main Southern line or by other routes to bring it into closer touch with Victoria will bear closer investigation to-day than hitherto, and there are now many more alternative routes to be considered. The latest route proposed is one through Orbost via Bombala to Canberra, which would be a national railway, in which the Commonwealth Government and the States of New South Wales and V[?]ria would be interested financially.

title: PLANS FOR CANBERRA Roman Catholic Church START IN NEW YEAR Early in the New Year, a commencement will be made by the Roman Catholic Church of a comprehensive scheme to cater for Canberra and its environs. The foundations are to be laid in July of a school, church, and of a convent in Canberra, and of a large hall in Queanbeyan. On the occasion of the laying of the foundation stones, the Archbishops of Sydney and Melbourne and the Bishop of Goulburn will visit Canberra. The Church has secured three fine sites in the city area, one of which is a cathedral site on the northern bank of the Molonglo River.

title: DEVELOPMENT OF CANBERRA The Commission's Plans NO EXPANSION TOWARDS QUEANBEYAN In view of the conflicting statements regarding the future development of Canberra, and the misapprehension under which many people labour regarding the manner of its development, "The Canbena Times" has secured by interview with the members of the Federal Capital Commission, some well defined statements regarding the future of the national capital. Mr. J. H. Butters, Chief Commission 21, and Sir John Harrison and Mr. C. H. Gorman, the Advisory Commissioners, are unanimous regarding the policy which the Commission will follow immediately and the general policy for the development of Canberra which is to be carried on in the distant future. Expansion in every manner away from the direction of Queanbeyan, preference to products of and labour resident in the Federal Capital Territory, comprehensive housing schemes for workmen, and a study of Canberra's every possible want for the next century, are cardinal features enunciated in the interviews.

title: LOOKING AHEAD FUTURE DEVELOPMENT OF CANBERRA BIG PROGRAMME FOR NEW COMMITTEE To look into the future to gauge the developmental requirements of Canberra in relation to the estimated increase in population, to prepare expert advice upon important phases of city development, and generally to pave the way for the inevitable-expansion of the Federal Capital—these are the functions of the recently-constituted Development Committee of the Federal Capital Commission. One of the first—and most important—tasks to engage the attention of the Committee, of whom Sir John Butters is chairman, and Col. P. T. Owen the Deputy Chairman, will be the preparation of an estimate of the population of the city at the end of the current year, a further estimate of the population at the end of the second wave of civil servants, and a calculation of the population of Canberra five years hence.

title: RAILWAY PROJECTS FOR NORTHERN SUBURBS New Line Surveyed North Of River REVIVING YASS CANBERRA LINE A new railway route has been surveyed north of the Molonglo River, which is proposed by the Federal Capital Commission to replace the existing city railway in the Griffin plan of Canberra. Railway projects of Canberra were discussed at a conference held at the week end between the Minister for Home and Territories, Mr. Marr, and Sir John Butters, Chief Commissioner. If the new line is approved, it will serve not only to connect the Northern suburbs of Canberra with the railway, but may act as the first portion of the Yass-Canberra line. With the realisation that Canberra is not accessible readily by rail to Melbourne and other State capitals, construction of the Yass-Canberra line is likely to be referred again to the Public Works Committee for report.

title: STOCK CLEARED FROM RIVER FLATS Heavy falls in the basin of the Molonglo River above Captain's Flat have have caused a sudden rise in the river and flood warnings were issued late yesterday in Canberra. At four o'clock yesterday afternoon four inches of rain had fallen at Captain's Flat where the river was in flood, and it is expected that the flood waters will reach Canberra this morning. Owners of stock on the river flats around Canberra were warned immediately to remove their stock from danger. Owing to the low state of the Molonglo, it is expected that the flood will have lost much of its force before reaching Canberra.

title: CANBERRA STORM SWEPT DAMAGE TO CITY ROADS MOLONGLO FLOOD DANGER PASSES A heavy downpour in and around Canberra on Saturday afternoon was responsible for dislocation of city and rural traffic for some hours, besides considerable damage to city streets in the Southern suburbs. Immediate danger of a flood in the Molonglo River passed yesterday. The flood warning sent from Captain's Flat on Friday was found to be unnecessary on Saturday morning when the river fell five feet at the mining settlement and the flood waters lost their force before reaching Canberra late on Saturday afternoon. Heavy rain fell at Captain's Flat on Saturday and although the river again rose, it is now reuming to normal.

title: RUSSELL HILL COMMISSION OUTLINES POLICY WHY SETTLEMENT MUST GO MOLONGLO TO FOLLOW LATER The Chief Commissioner yesterday outlined the policy of the Commission regarding the Russel Hill Settlement, and indicated that for the present, some of the residences would be permitted to remain for a period, but that the settlement must go, and that the Molonglo Settlement would not be continued any longer than could be helped. He said that of 120 houses at Russell Hill originally, there were 91 left last week-end, and eleven families would be moved this week-end. Of the balance, only about eighteen houses could be considered as passable habitations, and the occupants of the remainder would be moved to better quarters before the winter.
